sheets: Kendall DL use in cardiac monitoring associated with Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting (CABG)
Budget impact analysis in the United States of America
Introduction to working with the model
1. This computer model uses a Markov model to simulate progression of a cohort of patients who undergo CABG and received ECG monitoring with either disposable or reusable leads
2. Default values in the model are derived from peer-reviewed published literature and details can be found by clicking the information button on each page
3. Values that can be updted by the user are indicated by a light green background
4. Cells containing automatically calculated values cannot be altered and have a grey background
5. The model can be reset to default values using the reset button each page
6. Please navigate the model using the menu on the left-hand side
7. If there are any questions, please contact Coreva Scientific and provide the model title and version

Final result and econmic analysis from the Synergy Between Percutaneous Coronary Intervention With TAXUS and Cardiac Surgery (SYNTAX) trial, which enrolled 870 CABG patients between 2005 and 2007. Post procedural costs were taken from 43,866 SYNTAX eligible patients in the 2010 Medicare Povider Review database. The cost year was 2010.

Retrospective review of admissions to 5 types of ICU unit over the course of 2013. Costs are assumed to be 2013 costs and costs used are those for the cardiac surgery ICU. The additional cost of mechanical ventilation is provided in the supplement, and ranges from $193 per day in the medical ICU to $831 per day in the surgical ICU. The basecase value is $693 for the cariac ICU.

Retrospective review of admissions to 5 types of ICU unit over the course of 2013. Costs are assumed to be 2013 costs and costs used are those for the cardiac surgery ICU. Costs were provided for Day 1 ($5,166), Day 2 ($2,060), and Day 3-30 ($2,325). The latter is used as the median value and confidence intervals are the provided IQR.

Includes all operating and non-operating expenses for registered US community hospitals, defined as nonfederal short-term general and other special hospitals whose facilities and services are available to the public. Costs are in 2015 USD. Variance is assumed to be 1/10 of the base case value

Based on an annual salary of $65,000 and a 33% overhead. The upper and lower bound are assuming that the base salary ($65,000) varies by $10,000 in either direction and then the 33% overhead is applied. The number of nursing hours per year is taken to be 2,058 as per Lord 2006

Report for the US Department of Health and Human Services that analysed Medicare use of nursing and care facilities. The mean length of stay in a skilled nursing facility was 27 days, with a mean of $330 per day, with pricing in 2008 USD. The range is taken to be from the lowest mean cost ($46.6 per day for home help) to the highest mean cost (1,318 per day for long-term care hospitals).

Financial analysis of SSIs at Johns Hopkins Health System acute care hospitals in Maryland, including admissions from January 1, 2007 to December 31, 2010. SSIs increased healthcare costs but reduced the daily cost of care by $132 per day. Currency year not provided and so assumed to be 2010, the last year of analysis

This retrospective cohort study analysed SSIs reported between December 31, 2004 to December 31, 2010 in commercial insurer claims data. SSIs within 90 days post-procedure were identified and non-serious infectoins were those not during hospitalization or requiring surgery. Non-serious breast reconstruction surgeries were sued as the proxy for CABG, as these surgeries are also in the thorax. Non-serious SSIs cost $2,425 (591, 3,677) in 2014 USD

Financial analysis of SSIs at Johns Hopkins Health System acute care hospitals in Maryland, including admissions from January 1, 2007 to December 31, 2010. SSIs increased healthcare costs but reduced the daily cost of care by $132 per day. Currency year not provided and so assumed to be 2010, the last year of analysis

Retrospective analysis of propensity-score matched adult patients who underwent cardiac surgery between September 2008 and August 2012 at Staten Island University Hospital. Patient readmission was found to have a median cost of $21,100 and an IQR of $13,500 to $37,400. The currency year was not provided and was assumed to be 2012 USD as 2012 was the last year of data collection.
Mortality is assumed to have no direct cost to the facility
